## Example 3 — Convert Between Radical and Exponential Forms

### Step 1: Exponential to Radical

8^(1/5) = √[5]{8}

4^(2/7) = √[7]{4²} = √[7]{16}

(x³)^(3/2) = √[2]{(x³)³} = √[2]{x⁹} = x⁴√[2]{x}

### Step 2: Radical to Exponential

√17 = 17^(1/2)

√[3]{5xy²} = (5xy²)^(1/3)

√[4]{625x²} = (625x²)^(1/4) = 5x^(1/2)

## Example 4 — Real-World Applications

### Step 1: Orbiting Planets

The distance in millions of miles is given by √[3]{6t²}, where t is days to orbit.

In exponential form: (6t²)^(1/3)

### Step 2: Depreciation

The depreciation rate is 1 − (T/P)^(1/n).

For an 8-year-old car originally purchased for $52,425:
1 − (T/P)^(1/8) = 1 − (T/52425)^(1/8)

## Example 5 — Evaluate Expressions with Rational Exponents

### Step 1: Positive Exponents

27^(1/3) = 3

256^(1/4) = 4

### Step 2: Negative Exponents

16^(-3/2) = 1/(16^(3/2)) = 1/(4³) = 1/64

81^(-1/4) = 1/(81^(1/4)) = 1/3

### Step 3: Mixed Exponents

1024^(3/5) = (1024^(1/5))³ = 2³ = 8

16^(-5/4) = 1/(16^(5/4)) = 1/((16^(1/4))^5) = 1/(2⁵) = 1/32

## Example 6 — Simplify Products and Powers

### Step 1: Multiply Same Bases

x^(1/3) · x^(2/5) = x^(1/3 + 2/5) = x^(5/15 + 6/15) = x^(11/15)

### Step 2: Negative Exponents

b^(-3/4) = 1/b^(3/4)

y^(-4/5) = 1/y^(4/5)

